<paragraph id="0E94941537ECFDDA2293DD18C705F244" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F75FA3A1E0C9DADA8AE3DA86E16F0880" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicName id="DF2C5074E464F33DCE6A547E3F9FE680" authorityName="Gómez-Zapata &amp; Haelewaters &amp; Quijada &amp; Pfister &amp; Aime" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Gómez-Zapata &amp; Haelewaters &amp; Quijada &amp; Pfister &amp; Aime" baseAuthorityYear="2021" class="Leotiomycetes" family="Hemiphacidiaceae" genus="Cenangium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cenangium colensoi" order="Helotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="colensoi">
<emphasis id="D899EBF15B6AEC9C0C05DBC0DF5BAC32" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Cenangium colensoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is described from dead leaves of 
<taxonomicName id="95C3725F3DFEE75C4BB97239E7CB8784" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asparagaceae" genus="Cordyline" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cordyline" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="3A69953C89298977201147B369DC2534" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Cordyline</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. (
<taxonomicName id="B98BEBB8094662A3EE642AAA6F171315" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asparagaceae" genus="Cordyline" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="order">Asparagales</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4F6E2FC1D87E756676DB20D9AAC5C386" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asparagaceae" genus="Cordyline" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="family">Asparagaceae</taxonomicName>
) in New Zealand (
<bibRefCitation id="98F1B0D08C47574F6EC2911057F075CE" author="Hooker, JD" journalOrPublisher="Lovell Reeve, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" refId="B46" refString="Hooker, JD, 1855. The botany of the Antarctic Voyage of H.M. discovery ships Erebus and Terror, in the years 1839-1843. II. Flora Novae-Zealandiae. Part II. Flowerless plants. Lovell Reeve, London" title="The botany of the Antarctic Voyage of H. M. discovery ships Erebus and Terror, in the years 1839 - 1843. II. Flora Novae-Zealandiae. Part II. Flowerless plants." year="1855">Hooker 1855</bibRefCitation>
). The host had been mistakenly reported as 
<taxonomicName id="351F07C955475FF4AF5A82B1207B8EB9" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asphodelaceae" genus="Phormium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Phormium" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B120CA3DA2F19799FE1F0A2C14A164AA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Phormium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="C1FEDF2931B6AB8D82377B5127958240" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asphodelaceae" genus="Phormium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="order">Asparagales</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="F47AEC392F189B039CBF6F4EF89E1771" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asphodelaceae" genus="Phormium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="family">Asphodelaceae</taxonomicName>
) by Berkeley in 
<bibRefCitation id="CFDCEB82C10CAC492F6434CA3971B5E8" author="Hooker, JD" journalOrPublisher="Lovell Reeve, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" refId="B46" refString="Hooker, JD, 1855. The botany of the Antarctic Voyage of H.M. discovery ships Erebus and Terror, in the years 1839-1843. II. Flora Novae-Zealandiae. Part II. Flowerless plants. Lovell Reeve, London" title="The botany of the Antarctic Voyage of H. M. discovery ships Erebus and Terror, in the years 1839 - 1843. II. Flora Novae-Zealandiae. Part II. Flowerless plants." year="1855">Hooker (1855)</bibRefCitation>
and only recently corrected after re-study of the type collection (
<bibRefCitation id="F94A797714EDABDA96D31D73CC3A2571" author="Landcare Research" journalOrPublisher="Desray, Paris" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" publicationUrl="https://nzfungi2.landcareresearch.co.nz/default.aspx?selected=NameDetails&amp;TabNum=0&amp;NameId=1CB1B798-36B9-11D5-9548-00D0592D548C" refId="B65" refString="Landcare Research, 2020. Collection details. Pseudopeziza colensoi (Berk.) Massee (1896) [1895-97]. https://nzfungi2.landcareresearch.co.nz/default.aspx?selected=NameDetails&amp;TabNum=0&amp;NameId=1CB1B798-36B9-11D5-9548-00D0592D548C" title="Collection details. Pseudopeziza colensoi (Berk.) Massee (1896) [1895 - 97]." url="https://nzfungi2.landcareresearch.co.nz/default.aspx?selected=NameDetails&amp;TabNum=0&amp;NameId=1CB1B798-36B9-11D5-9548-00D0592D548C" year="2020">Landcare Research 2020</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="D67E01A783E76CCDDC4FD8B502B9AF95" authorityName="Gómez-Zapata &amp; Haelewaters &amp; Quijada &amp; Pfister &amp; Aime" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Gómez-Zapata &amp; Haelewaters &amp; Quijada &amp; Pfister &amp; Aime" baseAuthorityYear="2021" class="Leotiomycetes" family="Hemiphacidiaceae" genus="Cenangium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cenangium colensoi" order="Helotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="colensoi">
<emphasis id="E5C6D56DBE50681181A9FE28C10D49E1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Cenangium colensoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was later combined in 
<taxonomicName id="FFF1705A164BAC0EC48BDBADE9843FF4" authorityName="Fuckel" authorityYear="1870" class="Leotiomycetes" family="Hemiphacidiaceae" genus="Pseudopeziza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Pseudopeziza" order="Helotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="12DF2369862E87357FDDAE45852FB8D0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Pseudopeziza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and described in more detail by 
<bibRefCitation id="13DF84A6AB19AE7EF1823DC84DB1AD97" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00812.x" author="Massee, GE" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" pagination="463 - 524" refId="B70" refString="Massee, GE, 1896. Redescriptions of Berkeley's types of fungi. Journal of the Linnean Society 31: 463 - 524, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00812.x" title="Redescriptions of Berkeley's types of fungi." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00812.x" volume="31" year="1896">Massee (1896)</bibRefCitation>
. Both authors commented on the watery-grey disc and brownish receptacle of the apothecia. The apothecia develop among the rigid vascular bundles of the epidermis, first covered by the cuticle, then erumpent and opening by a narrow slit, becoming discoid when mature (
<bibRefCitation id="9F2A4BE04B15FD384D55AAE8C65A6B57" author="Hooker, JD" journalOrPublisher="Lovell Reeve, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" refId="B46" refString="Hooker, JD, 1855. The botany of the Antarctic Voyage of H.M. discovery ships Erebus and Terror, in the years 1839-1843. II. Flora Novae-Zealandiae. Part II. Flowerless plants. Lovell Reeve, London" title="The botany of the Antarctic Voyage of H. M. discovery ships Erebus and Terror, in the years 1839 - 1843. II. Flora Novae-Zealandiae. Part II. Flowerless plants." year="1855">Hooker 1855</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9151407E2DF9382F9AC9DFE0542A38B4" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00812.x" author="Massee, GE" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" pagination="463 - 524" refId="B70" refString="Massee, GE, 1896. Redescriptions of Berkeley's types of fungi. Journal of the Linnean Society 31: 463 - 524, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00812.x" title="Redescriptions of Berkeley's types of fungi." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00812.x" volume="31" year="1896">Massee 1896</bibRefCitation>
). The habit of this fungus fits well with typical macromorphological features of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="52071735B9DC8AC41F6993E569C53845" class="Leotiomycetes" family="Clavicipitaceae" genus="Trochila" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Trochila" order="Helotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="295290C3E77C908168CED9CA2FBF6753" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Trochila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
- a dark brown to black receptacle, which develops beneath the host tissues and eventually becomes erumpent to expose the hymenium by splitting along radial lines or by its splitting into lobes (von 
<bibRefCitation id="428E7FDFCE71C7DB08C33E88FB7881ED" author="Hoehnel, F von" journalOrPublisher="Annales Mycologici" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" pagination="330 - 334" refId="B45" refString="Hoehnel, F von, 1917. Ueber die Gattung Trochila Fries. Annales Mycologici 15: 330 - 334" title="Ueber die Gattung Trochila Fries." volume="15" year="1917">
<normalizedToken id="ABBA745E1CF0A7FCC382687282448447" originalValue="Höhnel">Hoehnel</normalizedToken>
1917
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="375C61B117E874D08D7D4E704B7A750B" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0007-1536(64)80002-4" author="Greenhalgh, G" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the British Mycological Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" pagination="311 - 320" refId="B33" refString="Greenhalgh, G, Morgan-Jones, G, 1964. Some species of Trochila and an undescribed discomycete on leaves of Prunus laurocerasus. Transactions of the British Mycological Society 47: 311 - 320, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/S0007-1536(64)80002-4" title="Some species of Trochila and an undescribed discomycete on leaves of Prunus laurocerasus." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0007-1536(64)80002-4" volume="47" year="1964">Greenhalgh and Morgan-Jones 1964</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="00FD34DD95135317733364FBA5D7F1C4" author="Dennis, RWG" journalOrPublisher="Cramer, Vaduz, Liechtenstein" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" refId="B19" refString="Dennis, RWG, 1978. British Ascomycetes. J. Cramer, Vaduz, Liechtenstein" title="British Ascomycetes. J." year="1978">Dennis 1978</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="F9339EB827C0101A6883FAF05408127C" author="Baral, H-O" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" refId="B6" refString="Baral, H-O, Marson, G, 2005. In vivo veritas. Over 10000 images of fungi and plants (microscopical drawings, water colour plates, photo macro- &amp; microphotographs), with materials on vital taxonomy and xerotolerance. Ed. 3. Privately distributed DVD-ROM." title="In vivo veritas. Over 10000 images of fungi and plants (microscopical drawings, water colour plates, photo macro- &amp; microphotographs), with materials on vital taxonomy and xerotolerance. Ed. 3. Privately distributed DVD-ROM." year="2005">Baral and Marson 2005</bibRefCitation>
). Microscopically, 
<taxonomicName id="EBABD4ABA092648D60456310B81704EB" genus="P." lsidName="P. colensoi" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="colensoi">
<emphasis id="D8A8A616745407F51FF7E4A0796EAF31" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">P. colensoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described with a parenchymatous excipulum (angular-globose or isodiametric cells), hyaline under the hymenium and dark brown at the cortex (Berkeley in 
<bibRefCitation id="5CDF00D6ACE3E9ED9201F9CE96DE9988" author="Hooker, JD" journalOrPublisher="Lovell Reeve, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" refId="B46" refString="Hooker, JD, 1855. The botany of the Antarctic Voyage of H.M. discovery ships Erebus and Terror, in the years 1839-1843. II. Flora Novae-Zealandiae. Part II. Flowerless plants. Lovell Reeve, London" title="The botany of the Antarctic Voyage of H. M. discovery ships Erebus and Terror, in the years 1839 - 1843. II. Flora Novae-Zealandiae. Part II. Flowerless plants." year="1855">Hooker 1855</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="40FD648C6A0E4332A240B425079F126C" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00812.x" author="Massee, GE" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" pagination="463 - 524" refId="B70" refString="Massee, GE, 1896. Redescriptions of Berkeley's types of fungi. Journal of the Linnean Society 31: 463 - 524, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00812.x" title="Redescriptions of Berkeley's types of fungi." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00812.x" volume="31" year="1896">Massee 1896</bibRefCitation>
), which is also in agreement with the excipular features of 
<taxonomicName id="5A7BF5C852E937DCC710112F70D372F4" class="Leotiomycetes" family="Clavicipitaceae" genus="Trochila" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Trochila" order="Helotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="663283C71664A3BCA8DE67A3A58A9481" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Trochila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species. Finally, the hymenium of 
<taxonomicName id="C427F6C511A8B2D9856043EA53A5A7AA" genus="P." lsidName="P. colensoi" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="colensoi">
<emphasis id="F7BA91E8819C303E55F34E45351E04FD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">P. colensoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described as composed of inamyloid, 8-spored asci with elliptical hyaline ascospores and slender paraphyses (
<emphasis id="836368A0F0EAB0D5D1DDC246F689993D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">op. cit.</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="74B9A4E776B8CC4F51ABD26595F22571" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">
In 2018, P.R. Johnston collected two specimens (PDD:112240, PDD:112242, 
<bibRefCitation id="6693DE6355D6A5540CD306C902C9BBEA" author="Landcare Research" journalOrPublisher="Desray, Paris" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" publicationUrl="https://nzfungi2.landcareresearch.co.nz/default.aspx?selected=NameDetails&amp;TabNum=0&amp;NameId=1CB1B798-36B9-11D5-9548-00D0592D548C" refId="B65" refString="Landcare Research, 2020. Collection details. Pseudopeziza colensoi (Berk.) Massee (1896) [1895-97]. https://nzfungi2.landcareresearch.co.nz/default.aspx?selected=NameDetails&amp;TabNum=0&amp;NameId=1CB1B798-36B9-11D5-9548-00D0592D548C" title="Collection details. Pseudopeziza colensoi (Berk.) Massee (1896) [1895 - 97]." url="https://nzfungi2.landcareresearch.co.nz/default.aspx?selected=NameDetails&amp;TabNum=0&amp;NameId=1CB1B798-36B9-11D5-9548-00D0592D548C" year="2020">Landcare Research 2020</bibRefCitation>
) on leaves of 
<taxonomicName id="990692609ED6AE578407966BA79FEF35" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asparagaceae" genus="Cordyline" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cordyline australis" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis id="7DABAEB92E45073DD5612DAADCF480AE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Cordyline australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="2FD544943174889C90034B230E346BF1" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asparagaceae" genus="Cordyline" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="family">Asparagaceae</taxonomicName>
). The morphology, ecology (host), and locality of these new collections agree with 
<taxonomicName id="AC3EFC9E3CBB5649DFDA70560B893F4D" genus="P." lsidName="P. colensoi" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="colensoi">
<emphasis id="0FB6CED4322225BCA93007312CC0A096" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">P. colensoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The photographs of both specimens reveal features such as guttules in ascospores and paraphyses, protruding hyaline cells in the cortical layer of the upper flank and margin, and hyaline gelatinized hyphae covering the dark globose-angular cells of the ectal excipulum at the base and lower flanks. The latter excipular feature of the receptacle is reminiscent of 
<bibRefCitation id="525DB63781E9ABD42DD3202ABD0F63DF" author="Zhuang, WY" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" pagination="121 - 124" refId="B108" refString="Zhuang, WY, 1990. Calycellinopsis Xishuangbanna gen. et sp. nov. (Dermateaceae), a petiole-inhabiting fungus from China. Mycotaxon 38: 121 - 124" title="Calycellinopsis Xishuangbanna gen. et sp. nov. (Dermateaceae), a petiole-inhabiting fungus from China." volume="38" year="1990">
<normalizedToken id="1FE3DAB40205B768CE688664240397DE" originalValue="Zhuang’s">Zhuang's</normalizedToken>
(1990)
</bibRefCitation>
description of 
<taxonomicName id="C0401E4EC010D2E976F4872A2030DB85" authorityName="Gómez-Zapata &amp; Haelewaters &amp; Quijada &amp; Pfister &amp; Aime" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Gómez-Zapata &amp; Haelewaters &amp; Quijada &amp; Pfister &amp; Aime" baseAuthorityYear="2021" class="Leotiomycetes" family="Dermateaceae" genus="Calycellinopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Calycellinopsis xishuangbanna" order="Helotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="xishuangbanna">
<emphasis id="61EA9EA3705098373084CA44A44416DE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Calycellinopsis xishuangbanna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. An ITS sequence of this species was generated from the recent material (PDD:112240) and included in the 
<taxonomicName id="93B4FC88CEFB88B37AAB23212484D913" class="Leotiomycetes" family="Dermateaceae" genus="Calycellinopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="" order="Helotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="class">Leotiomycetes</taxonomicName>
-wide ITS phylogeny of 
<bibRefCitation id="6B859F1D2E010AD91840F8AB33A930FC" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1186/s43008-019-0002-x" author="Johnston, PR" journalOrPublisher="IMA Fungus" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" pagination="1 - 22" refId="B52" refString="Johnston, PR, Quijada, L, Smith, CA, Baral, H-O, Hosoya, T, Baschien, C, Paertel, K, Zhuang, K-Y, Haelewaters, D, Park, D, Carl, S, Lopez-Giraldez, F, Wang, Z, Townsend, JP, 2019. A multigene phylogeny toward a new phylogenetic classification of Leotiomycetes. IMA Fungus 10: 1 - 22, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1186/s43008-019-0002-x" title="A multigene phylogeny toward a new phylogenetic classification of Leotiomycetes." url="https://doi.org/10.1186/s43008-019-0002-x" volume="10" year="2019">Johnston et al. (2019)</bibRefCitation>
. Their results and those in this study (Figs 
<figureCitation id="E08909FFF13557B55158427371E8A34A" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. The best-scoring ML tree (- lnL = 87544.854) of Cenangiaceae, Cordieritidaceae, Rutstroemiaceae, Sclerotiniaceae, and the Piceomphale clade, reconstructed from a concatenated six-locus dataset (SSU, ITS, LSU, rpb 1, rpb 2, and tef 1). For each node, the ML bootstrap value (if ≥ 70) is presented above or in front of the branch leading to that node. The arrow denotes the genus Trochila. Species with an asterisk (*) are treated in the Taxonomy section." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys..62046.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/507850" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="2834DF24B4A228EC3F50A6901613EC6E" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. The best-scoring ML tree (- lnL = 5225.551) of Cenangiaceae, reconstructed from a concatenated ITS-LSU dataset. For each node, the ML bootstrap value (if ≥ 70) is presented above the branch leading to that node. Species treated in the Taxonomy section are highlighted with gray shading." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys..62046.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/507851" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">2</figureCitation>
) show that 
<taxonomicName id="F6306491BC9A4DD41C78D0BE25B9E147" genus="P." lsidName="P. colensoi" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="colensoi">
<emphasis id="C46949DD4673F559BBC1C20DB037A8C7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">P. colensoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is placed among species of 
<taxonomicName id="109ADD7AB0614691BFAAD79976F58DD0" class="Leotiomycetes" family="Clavicipitaceae" genus="Trochila" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Trochila" order="Helotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8713018986F31C89A5B471884F9980E7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Trochila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
